IMHO It would be a great if Blazor used Roslyn to dynamically create in memory implementation of JavaScriptInterop based of c# abstract classes, eg.

`
namespace someJavascriptNamespace {
public abstract class someJavaScriptInterop { 
public abstract bool someJavaScriptMethod(string stringParameter, bool boolParameter);
...
}
}

/// use roslyn to generate and compile the code that calls/invokes the javascript  
TJavaScriptInteropDefinition GenerateImplementation<TJavaScriptInteropDefinition>( );
`
/// calling the generated implementation 
var result = GenerateImplementation<TJavaScriptInteropDefinition>( )
.someJavaScriptMethod("",true);

Let's suppose I have markup as shown below:

```
<MyComponent>
    <RowTemplate>
        <div>"@SomeExpression"<div>
    </RowTemplate>
    <SomeSettings Mode="Auto"/>
</MyComponent>
```

Currently, it is possible to manage where to render the nested markup:

```
public class MyComponent : BlazorDataComponent 
{
	public RenderFragment ChildContent { get; set; }
        protected override void BuildRenderTree(RenderTreeBuilder builder)
        {
        	// ...
        	// Some render tree building 
        	// ...
            ChildContent(builder); // here
            // ...
            // Some render tree building 
            // ...
        }
}
```

If methods of the RenderTreeBuilder class (the type of "builder" in the example above) were virtual, it would allow us to affect Blazor's process of tree building.
Derive from RenderTreeBuilder and override all required methods:

```
public class MyRenderTreeBuilder : RenderTreeBuilder
{
    public MyRenderTreeBuilder(Renderer renderer) : base(renderer)
    {
    }

    public override void OpenElement(int sequence, string elementName) 
    {
    	if(elementName == "SomeSettings") { ... }
    	if(elementName == "RowTemplate") { ... }
    	...
    }

    public override ...
}
```

Inject the derived MyRenderTreeBuilder into BuildRenderTree method:

```
public class MyComponent : BlazorDataComponent 
{
	public RenderFragment ChildContent { get; set; }
        protected override void BuildRenderTree(RenderTreeBuilder builder)
        {
        	var myBuilder = new MyRenderTreeBuilder();
            ChildContent(myBuilder); // Process the tree internally and pass the processed tree to the Blazor
        	
        	// ...

        }
}
```

Process the tree internally and pass the processed tree to the Blazor.

If this were done, we would be granted a powerful capability to build rich components.

First, apologies that this is such a massive PR. It involves every level of the system, including tooling, compilation, component APIs, rendering/diffing, and JS interop. I'm providing the following information in the hope that it will be useful when writing docs for these features.

This PR provides two related features:

### Capturing references to elements

Example:

```
    <input ref="username" ... />

    @functions {
        ElementRef username;
    }
```

As far as .NET code is concerned, an `ElementRef` is an opaque handle. The *only* thing you can do with it is pass it through to JS code via JSON-marshalled interop. When you do so, the JS-side code receives an `HTMLElement` instance which it can use in normal DOM APIs.

For example, if you registered the following:

```js
Blazor.registerFunction('MyLib.FocusElement', function (element) {
    element.focus();
});
```

... then in .NET code you could also define an extension method:

```csharp
namespace MyLib
{
    public static class MyLibElementRefExtensions
    {
        public static void Focus(this ElementRef elementRef)
        {
            RegisteredFunction.Invoke<object>("MyLib.FocusElement", elementRef);
        }
    }
}
```

Now you can focus inputs in any of your components:

```
    @using MyLib

    <input ref="username" />
    <button onclick="@SetFocus">Set focus</button>

    @functions {
        ElementRef username;

        void SetFocus()
        {
            username.Focus();
        }
    }
```

*Important*: The `username` variable will only be populated after the component has rendered and its output includes the `<input>` element, because until then there is nothing to reference. If you try to pass an unpopulated `ElementRef` to JS code, then the JS code will receive `null`. Once we implement support for an "after render" lifecycle method, you'll be able to put code in it that lifecycle method that, for example, sets the initial focus on an element as soon as the component is first rendered.

**Use case**

The intended use cases for this feature are:

1. Integration with third-party UI libraries (such as Bootstrap) whose APIs sometimes require you to pass them references to elements for initialization
2. Calling DOM APIs that represent "commands" such as `focus` or `play` (but *not* APIs that are for constructing content, such as setting text).

It is **strongly not recommended** to use this as a way of populating the DOM routinely in cases where you could instead use Blazor's normal declarative rendering. Declarative rendering is strongly preferred because it knows how to update automatically at the correct time with minimal diffs.

### Capturing references to components

Similarly, you can use `ref` on child components:

```
    <MyLoginDialog ref="loginDialog" ... />

    @functions {
        MyLoginDialog loginDialog;

        void OnSomething()
        {
            loginDialog.Show();
        }
    }
```

As you can see, in this case the value type is not `ElementRef`, but instead is the type of the component being referenced. Again, the `loginDialog` field will only be non-`null` once the component is rendered, because until then there is no child component to reference.

*Note:* This is not a JS interop feature. It's not expected that you will pass instances of Blazor components to JS code, because the JS code would not be able to do anything meaningful with it. It's only expected that you'll use the references in .NET code.

**Use case**

The intended use case is to allow parent components to issue commands to child components such as "show" or "reset".

Even then, architecturally it's a compromise because it would be cleaner still for your child components to be stateless (that is, not acting on any state other than their parameters) and in that case it's not even theoretically possible for it to make sense to issue an "action" other than by changing their child's parameters, in which case you don't need `ref` at all.

It is **strongly not recommended** that you use `ref` as a way of mutating the state of child components. Instead, always use normal declarative parameters to pass data to child components. This will cause child components to re-render at the correct times automatically. We are moving towards changing how parameters on components are represented so that by default they are encapsulated and not possible to read/write from outside.

### Notes for PR reviewers

**Perf**

I had to introduce a new `RenderTreeFrame` type to hold a delegate that assigns the reference. This is because we can't obtain the reference during the render phase; we can only obtain it during diffing because that's when children are instantiated.

With current versions of C#, this means it will cause one allocation per `ref` per render. Later versions of C# that cache noncapturing lambda delegate instances will only require one allocation per `ref` per component (not per render).

That is, except for when it's a capturing lambda (e.g., `<div ref="someLoopVariable.SomeReference" />`. In this case there will always be more allocations, but I consider that enough of an edge case not to mind. Plus it's not like I have any reasonable alternative.

Other than that, it should be pretty neutral on perf.

**Issues**

* The `ref` tag helper doesn't show any intellisense if you prefix its value with `@` (e.g., `<div ref="@myThing" />`), even though it's fine without (e.g., `<div ref="myThing" />`). I have not been able to track down why this difference exists. The source map data *looks* correct. Would appreciate any insight from @rynowak on this! It does work correctly in runtime builds with or without `@`.
* The `ref` tag helper does show correct warning squigglies if you reference a nonexistent variable (e.g., `<div ref="somethingThatIsNotDefined" />`). But it does *not* show squigglies if you reference something of the wrong type (e.g., `<div ref="someIntField" />`). I know why, which is because in the generated code we can only associate the source token with either the assigned variable **or** the value we're assigning to it. In the case of a type mismatch, the error is associated with the value being assigned. I consider it more important to catch the "nonexistent variable" case. In both cases the runtime compiler output is correct and makes it easy to diagnose the error. I didn't find any trick to produce alternate design-time code that catches both error types using a single token.

I have the following code
```
@inherits MyCompBase

@for(var i=0; i< Counter;i++)
{
    <div onclick=@( x=>ItemClicked(i))>this is item @i</div>
}

using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Blazor.Components;
using System;

namespace WebApplication2.Shared
{
    public class MyCompBase : BlazorComponent
    {
        public int Counter { get; set; } = 4;
        public void ItemClicked(int value)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(value);
        }
    }
}
```
I expected it to write value "i" to be written to console when the div is clicked. it is always writing "4". what am I missing?
